                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>pay for them. Please let me know what I<lb/> owe you up to the present, and I will\n                hand<lb/> it to <persName>Mr Myers</persName> to whom I have spoken on<lb/> the\n                subject. Religious matters here are of<lb/> no importance, all is quiet. Your\n                    <date>April</date>\n                <hi rend=\"underline\">No</hi><lb/> caused a great consternation among a certain<lb/>\n                class who were delighted to find that these acts<lb/> were made known to the world,\n                altho' they are<lb/> not able to prevent them of course the Gleaner<lb/> has its\n                supporters as there are so many<lb/> who will do wrong in spite of every thing<lb/>\n                you will no doubt see how the Gleaner<lb/> answers for itself. Not one thing\n                satisfactory<lb/> because as you know <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> still we must do our\n                duty. The Letter<lb/> which he inserts is from one of the ladies<lb/> whom I refused\n                to marry. I have no<lb/> doubt that the Gleaner managed this<lb/> matter to be\n                    <add>?</add>\n                <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> but the truth was not stated therein and<lb/> if even all was\n                true, what right had<lb/>\n                <persName>Dr Eckman</persName> to marry her. He certainly does<lb/> not think I am\n                greater than he is to act<lb/> in opposition to a Law because I or<lb/> any man\n                ventures an opinion, which you<lb/> yourself can see how he shirks the question.</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3vt1h90n/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
            }
